ce:section.ce:para:
An electrochemical sensor's performance needs to be optimized in order to ensure proper operation. Using the Taguchi experimental design method, the research process was made time- and cost-efficient. Based on preliminary experiments, four influential factors including the amount of GQDs, the concentration of HAuCl4, deposition time, and deposition potential were evaluated and optimized at four levels (
Table S1
). According Taguchi L16 orthogonal array (OA) design, 16 experiments were performed. As a response, the average oxidation peaks current of FLU at −0.6 V was taken after triplicate experiments. Table S2 presents the computational results of 16 runs in the L16 orthogonal array and the average response obtained for each run. The mean responses of S/N ratios in terms of FLU oxidation peak current at each level of four factors are summarized in Table S3 . Consequently, the influence of the four factors on FLU oxidation peak current was ranked as follows: the concentration of HAuCl4 > deposition potential > amount of GQDs > deposition time. Also based on the S/N ratios in Table S3 , the best results were obtained in the following optimal conditions; the amount of GQDs 15 µL (level 3), the concentration of HAuCl4 2.0 mM (level 3), deposition time 1800 s (level 2), and deposition potential −0.3 V (level 1). For better visualizing the effect of the factors on the FLU oxidation signal, the profiles of mean S/N ratios were analyzed (
Fig. S1
). According to this plot, the factor with the highest S/N ratio is at its optimal level. According to Table S3 , the main effects plot for the S/N ratio revealed the same results. Analysis of variance (ANOVA) was also performed in order to investigate the contribution ratio of each factor to the sensor response. It is statistically significant if the factor has a lower P-value. P-values above 0.05 are considered significant, while P-values below 0.05 are considered unsignificant. So, according to ANOVA analysis outputs, the most and least effective factors on the FLU oxidation peak current are the concentration of HAuCl4 and the deposition time which is in good agreement with the S/N ratio analysis results (
Table S4
).
